did.abstract: A collection of archival papers, audio-visual media, publications, artifacts, photographs, letters, and other documents connected to Hershman-Leeson's art works and projects created since the 1970s and through 2003.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Collections
relatedmaterial.p: Women art revolution : videotape interviews by Lynn Hershman-Leeson for film, 1990-2008, M1639. A digital collection containing the video interviews, as well as transcripts, is available online at http://lib.stanford.edu/women-art-revolution.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Lynn Hershman Leeson (b. 1941) is a performance artist and filmmaker who, in various media, has investigated the idea of selfhood and what establishes an individual as a sentient, gendered, unique person. Between the years of 1974 and 1978, Hershman Leeson spent much of her time performing as an alter ego, the character Roberta Breitmore. Much of the work--drawings, photographs, clothing, medical records, letters, etc.--Hershman Leeson produced during the Breitmore years related to the character's emotional and practical existences. Hershman Leeson seemed to be demonstrating that the two existences could and should not be easily separated--nor should the artist herself be easily separated from the character she created. Hershman Leeson's work in film, video, and new media has been equally focused toward exploring the ways that bodies interact and define themselves. Lorna (1983-84), described by the artist as "the first interactive video art disc," allowed the viewer to experience the emotions of the title character while also, at key points, making important decisions for her. The viewer was both entwined with and removed from Lorna's life. In the 1980s and 90s, Hershman continued to focus on new media, expanding her work in video and creating online environments that incorporated artificial intelligence. Concurrently, she began to direct feature films; her first film, Conceiving Ada (1997), situated the nineteenth-century computer science innovator Ada Lovelace in juxtaposition with the twentieth-century computer reality that she helped to create. A winner of numerous awards and honors for her contributions to art practice, Hershman Leeson is currently Chair of the Film Department at the San Francisco Art Institute. She is Professor Emerita at the University of California, Davis, and an A.D. White Professor at large at Cornell University. !Women Art Revolution reflects years of interviews that Hershman Leeson has compiled in order to tell the story of the feminist art movement in the artists' own words.

accessrestrict.head: Access to Collection
accessrestrict.p: Open for research. Audio-visual materials are not available in original format, and must be reformatted to a digital use copy.

userestrict.head: Publication Rights
userestrict.p: All requests to reproduce, publish, quote from, or otherwise use collection materials must be submitted in writing to the Head of Special Collections and University Archives, Stanford University Libraries, Stanford, California 94304-6064. Consent is given on behalf of Special Collections as the owner of the physical items and is not intended to include or imply permission from the copyright owner. Such permission must be obtained from the copyright owner, heir(s) or assigns. See: http://library.stanford.edu/depts/spc/pubserv/permissions.html.
Restrictions also apply to digital representations of the original materials. Use of digital files is restricted to research and educational purposes.

Miscellaneous correspondence re: Hershman credit as Artisitic Director for Running Fences (Photocopies) 1974-1977

Research and Development; includes Annual Report 1974, California Coastal Zone Commmission; Water Resources Development: California, 1975, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers; "Christo's Running Fence," statement of purpose and timeline prepared by Ernest C. Harris, senior staff engineer, Ken R. White Company; computation sheets for the stability and strength of the Running Fence, prepared by the Ken R. White Company; "Idea #2. Running Fence. Lynn Hershman 1982," collage composed of sketch with postcard annotations; "Running Fence co-sponsorship agreement regarding the purchase of Running Fence by the Running Fence Corporation; message to Ted Dougherty, Christo, Mary Abell and Peter Selz from Ernie H. regarding an engineering detail of the Running Fence. 1974-1977

Maps; includes Road map of Petaluma and Sonoma County with annotated route of the Running Fence and miscellaneous notes; blueprint map, detailing areas between Two Rock and Glen Ellen; blueprint map, detailing areas between Bodega Bay and Two Rock; blueprint map, detailing areas between Bodega Bay (Head)/Jenner and Two Rock; blueprint map, detailing areas between Valley Ford and Cotati; blueprint detailing property holdings along path of the Running Fence, with list of owners; large blueprint map detailing areas between Bodega Bay and Denman Flat, showijng route of the fence, adjacent roads and gates, location of truck, motor bikes, and foot monitors. ` 1974-1977

Contracts and Agreements; includes "Running Fence General Information:" report describing project and timeline of the legal history of the project; Use Permit application Sonoma County Planning Department with photocopied attachment title pages (no attached documents); Final Agenda North Central Coast Regional Commission, Thursday April 17, 1975 (Consent Calendar item d. Running Fence); Report of Test No. 2 Run B on a Prototype Section of Christo's Running Fence (Ken R. White Co. and A and H Builders); contract between Running Fence Corporation and Lynn Hershman as Associate Director, three contract definitions were changed and dated April 25, 1975, New York; Maysles Films, Inc. release form with signatures; California Coastal Zone Conservation Commission Agenda, 6/17/75 (Running Fence, item 8f); Easement Agreement between Edward H. and Jerrold E. Peterson and the Running Fence Corp., n.d.; Board of Supervisors County of Marin Agenda, 2/4/75 (Running Fence item #47); Agreement between Lynn Hershman and the Running Fence Corporation, detailing Hershman's terms and duties, dated 1/1/1974; "Application for Employment - Installation and Display Workers, Christo's Running Fence - Sonoma-Marin Counties," blank contract forms; "Executed Easement Agreements for Running Fence (From West to East)," lists parcel numbers, names and addresses. 1974-1977
